# The Decline in the Velocity of Money: Causes and Implications

The velocity of money, defined as the frequency at which one unit of currency is used to purchase domestically-produced goods and services within a given time period, has been a critical economic indicator for assessing the health and dynamism of an economy. It is typically calculated as the ratio of nominal Gross Domestic Product (GDP) to the money supply (V = PQ/M), where P is the price level, Q is the quantity of goods and services produced, and M is the money supply. A higher velocity indicates more transactions per unit of money, suggesting robust economic activity, whereas a declining velocity often signals economic stagnation or contraction.

Over the past two decades, and particularly since the global financial crisis of 2008 and the COVID-19 pandemic, the velocity of money in the United States has experienced a pronounced and sustained decline. This report aims to provide a detailed, comprehensive, and data-supported analysis of why the velocity of money has declined, drawing on multiple reputable sources to offer an objective understanding of the phenomenon.

---

## Overview of the Decline in Money Velocity

The velocity of both M1 and M2 money supplies in the U.S. has been declining for over a decade, reaching historic lows. Specifically, the velocity of M1 money stock is at its lowest level since 1975, and the velocity of M2 money stock is at its lowest since data recording began in 1959 ([Disruptive Investor, 2015](https://seekingalpha.com/article/3066146-why-money-velocity-continues-to-decline)).

The decline has been steady over the past 20 years, with a sharp acceleration during the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020. The pandemic-induced economic shock, combined with expansive monetary and fiscal policies, has created an environment where money supply has grown exponentially, yet the velocity of money has plummeted ([Demsher, 2021](https://usceconreview.com/2021/04/15/the-u-s-decline-in-money-velocity/)).

---

## Key Causes of the Decline in Money Velocity

### 1. **Expansionary Monetary Policy and Increased Money Supply**

A primary driver of declining velocity is the robust increase in the money supply (M1 and M2), which has outpaced nominal GDP growth. The Federal Reserve's disinflationary policies, including quantitative easing and near-zero interest rates, have significantly increased the money supply. For example, in 2020, the U.S. money supply grew by over 23% year-on-year, nearly double the prior peak growth rate ([Demsher, 2021](https://usceconreview.com/2021/04/15/the-u-s-decline-in-money-velocity/)).

According to the quantity theory of money, if the money supply grows faster than nominal GDP, the velocity of money will decline because there is more money circulating relative to the volume of transactions. This inverse relationship is a fundamental reason for the observed decline.

### 2. **Economic Uncertainty and Increased Savings**

The COVID-19 pandemic heightened economic uncertainty, leading consumers and businesses to increase their savings and reduce spending. This behavioral shift means that money is held longer and changes hands less frequently, directly reducing velocity. During peak COVID-19 lockdowns, core inflation actually fell by 0.4%, and headline inflation was negative at -1.1%, reflecting subdued spending despite increased money supply ([Demsher, 2021](https://usceconreview.com/2021/04/15/the-u-s-decline-in-money-velocity/)).

### 3. **Shift from Cash to Digital Payments and Changes in Payment Behavior**

The decline in the velocity of M1 money can be partly explained by the shift away from cash to cards and online payments. Digital payments, while increasing transaction efficiency, have altered the nature of money circulation. Banks and fintech companies have seen a transformation in payment behaviors, with more consumers adopting mobile wallets and online banking, especially accelerated by the pandemic ([The Financial Brand, 2020](https://thefinancialbrand.com/96502/coronavirus-covid-19-changing-banking-payments-digital-behavior-trends/)).

While this shift increases transaction volume in some respects, it also reduces the need for holding physical cash, which traditionally circulates faster. The net effect is a complex alteration of velocity dynamics, often contributing to lower measured velocity.

### 4. **Lack of Viable Investment and Spending Opportunities**

Despite the increase in money supply, much of the additional liquidity has remained in bank reserves rather than being actively deployed in the economy. This is due to a lack of viable uses for the cash, as economic growth opportunities have been limited by structural factors such as stagnation in conventional oil production and diminishing returns on capital investments ([D J Sims, 2016](https://economics.stackexchange.com/questions/10843/implications-of-declining-money-velocity)).

This liquidity glut has led to a situation where money sits idle, reducing the frequency of transactions and thus velocity.

### 5. **Demographic and Structural Economic Changes**

Long-term demographic trends, including aging populations, have contributed to more conservative spending and investment behaviors. Older populations tend to save more and spend less, which reduces the velocity of money. Additionally, structural changes in the economy, such as increased automation and shifts toward service-based industries, may also affect the velocity by changing transaction patterns and the nature of economic exchanges.

